    <p>My takeaway from this particular portion of code is that most environmental variables that you store should be in your back end, server side file. All environmental variables placed on your client side application can easily be found and are exposed. Integrating this API meant adding the fetch request to my front end application and adding the server side API call on the back end. I also learned how simple it can be to implement new features on an application. </p>
    <h3>React Portal</h3>
    <p>After giving a quick presentation on React Portals as a class assignment, I felt the need to implement them into my project. I referenced my notes from my presentation preparation and got this functioning fairly easily.</p>
    <p>Code Snippet Here</p>
    <p>What I learned from this section of code is that React portals are easy to add to your React application, HOWEVER, playing with styling here can be the deciding factor in making them wonderful or having them be super frustrating. I was initially confused as my react portal was coming into the DOM as expected, but it was not showing anything on the page. After some quick formatting and adding a background, I was able to add update functionality in my portal component which added a nice feel to my user interface. Another small thing to note is that while using React Hooks would be my preference any time I create an app with React, the documentation for most React items is written using older syntax that can make things feel convoluted.</p>
    <h3>React-Bootstrap</h3>
    <p>After using Bootstrap on another project and trying to avoid a styling framework in several other projects, I decided that the clean and consistent styling with the React-Bootstrap components were the way to go for this application. Styling is something that I always tend to spend a long time pondering, so having building blocks to get started was a major time saver for me.</p>
